Variation . Carapace length: males 4.8–6.7 (n= 37 ), females 5.1–7.75 (n= 25 ). Femur II: males 7.2–10.13 (n= 37 ), females 6.0– 9.1 (n= 25 ). Picks in the palpal femur: 5–7 . Spermathecae branches: 9–13 (typically 12 or less). Genitalic morphology is variable in both sexes (
Figs 64–85
).

Distribution . Central and Northeastern Brazil , in the states of Alagoas, Bahia, Ceará, Goiás, Maranhão, Pernambuco, Piauí and Tocantins (
Fig. 166
).

Natural history. This species is usually collected in Caatinga areas (
Figs 154–158
), where individuals lie beneath logs, stones or termite nests. This species is also known from Restinga vegetation (
Fig. 159
) and dry forest enclaves in the Cerrado domain. Specimens have been observed preying on cockroaches, small mygalomorph spiders and conspecifics. The observations on mating behavior mentioned above have been taken from a couple of this species from Morro do Chapéu, Bahia (
Fig. 44
). Eggsacs have been found attached to fallen logs, cave walls and living tree trunks. Twenty-five newly hatched individuals had between 1.19 and 1.37mm in carapace length.
